messages.content: **0. Abstract**
Erica awakens in some sort of black void. She can't see anything for a moment, but then Madakoe (from Q&A) shows up.
"Hello, Erica Furuda."
"Oh, hey." I get up, and check what I’m wearing.
This doesn't happen. Erica is unable to move.
I think of how this is a brilliant reference to a Madakoe gag.
Am I dreaming? I force myself to wake up.
"I guess that is what you think about a lot of the time. I'm pretty funny. I'm no Clem (AJ4), inventor of comedy, though."
"You could call this a dream. You could also not. You're not in control of when it ends. But there's really no reason for it to turn out being dragged out."
Madakoe >>>>>>>> Clem, honestly. Though Madakoe goes above everyone, obviously.

After a few more minutes in darkness, Erica awakens slouched against a wall. 

The room she woke up in was a perfect dodecagon, with 6 doors positioned equally across the sides each with a unique design inscribed next to it. In the center of the room was some kind of hatch with a massive 7 inscribed on it. Nobody else was in the room, awake or otherwise(this is the end of the chapter).
Klaud awakens in some sort of black void. His father, Tucker Reaction, is there. Just staring at him. An extended reaction shot.
He blinks repeatedly trying to make more sense of where he is.
Klaud Reaction cannot blink.
He tries to look away from Tucker.

Klaud Reaction cannot move.

"...Well. I guess you'd get caught in some sort of mess like this eventually."
“What is happening?!”
He tries to say.
He’s not sure if he can speak yet.
Strangely, he can speak.

"I can't say I'm not intrigued. You're pretty plain, appearance wise. But does something lie beneath? A lurking madness? Will you be an agent of chaos, or a straight man foil? Well... I have my takes. But it's probably best if you don't waste your time here, Klaud."
“Dad?? What are you talking about?”

"What do *you* think I'm talking about, kid? I'm sure with your knowledge of me, you have some theories of what I think of you. Hell, they're not even really theories. Just practical observation. Y'know what they say about perception."
“I don’t know if my observations apply considering you’re speaking as if you don’t know me.”

"Klaud, I'm your father, Tucker Reaction, and I hate you because you're gay. Come on."

The void is no longer. Klaud wakes up to the sound of seagulls crying, staring up at a blue sky.
((You're done the session woooo))
((STOP TAKING ME PLACES))
Rikarasu awakens in some sort of black void. There is nothing but what appears to be a reflection of herself.
"...Hello?"
*She looks around.* "I'm dreaming, aren't I? A distortion of reality... in a sense, a mystery in itself."
"Nothing but me and myself. A reflection. Should it be called Fainda, or...?"
*She then reaches out to the reflection as if to grab it.*
Rikarasu is unable to move.
The reflection can, however, and reaches out towards you, then stares at its (her?) hand.
"Can you speak?"
"Well, yes."
"Do you know who I am?"
She laughs. "I was going to ask the same thing, actually."
"My answer is that you're my reflection. A figment of me, or maybe another side."
"My name is Rikarasu Endo, but I go by Fainda Shinjitsu. Are you the same?"
"Uncanny. I am, yes."
"How about a quick quiz? That'll be easy for myself."
"Sure, I'll humor you."
"What was the name of the story where Detective Shinjitsu first appeared? The very original."
She accurately says this ((I can’t fuxking find if I sent it in DMs and if I didn’t it is officially now named “Fainda Shinjitsu and The House”))
((I do not think you did so lmao))
*She smiles.* "And what's the name of the decently noted online-only story with a modern incarnation of her as a secondary character? The one that's been on my mind lately?"

“That’s ‘The Grizwald Dispute’. I don’t think it’s been translated out of English yet, so that’s all I can call it.”

It’s amazing how omniscient translation never makes sentences weird.

"Right." *She thinks for a moment.* "So why was I suddenly reminded of it just now? Can you remember the name of the other character, from a different but related story, which a certain Tunisian girl claimed she shared?"

She tilts her head. “Madakoe Angiot. Y-“

Cutting whatever she was saying off, Rikarasu jolts upward in what seems like the same exact place. But it quickly becomes clear that this is just somewhere dark, not an existential void. She’s able to move again. ((End chapter and session))
Voreverl awakens in what appears to be a black void.
((Is there like, a floor, or,))
Voreverl can't perceive a floor, but is standing on something or other, not just in freefall.

Voreverl looks around frantically "What the!? Kidnapped twice in one day!? Or... Wait, is this the other world that planner guy talked about?? I was expecting something more conquerable... But if this is all it is then... What a fantastic betrayal! I'll have to write down the idea to trap someone in a void when I get home, I'm sure Eric would be real surprised by it! ...Though first I have to get out, I guess." Voreverl tries walking around to see if she can stumble upon anything other than just pure black.
There's a whole lot of not anything.

"Ugh... Okay, the evil scheme's effective, I get it, you're good at kidnappings. Does it really need to be drawn out. A good villain understands the importance of pacing! Maybe one of my minions can help, hopefully they weren't foolish enough to fall into the same trap as me... Which I purposefully fell into! To check if it was safe for them! Which if it wasn't I would let them fall into it anyway!" Voreverl yells this clarification to the sky that does not exist and then checks if she has the PDA on her.
The PDA is there.

She checks the earth-gc and is about to type a message asking where the others are, but hesitates upon seeing the initials for the messages from the others. She quickly puts the PDA away, she can handle this without the group chat. Voreverl continues walking and begins yelling out the names of her minions (Klaud, Viotto, Voreverl Jr.), hoping for a response.
Nothing. After some wandering, Voreverl awakens with a start in a tent with a bunch of unfamiliar people. ((YOU ARE PAUSED.))
Viotto is in the tundra. Everyone else is gone.
((oh god. oh fuck))
Viotto thrusts his paper into the air. "SHEEV-"
He blinks.
Wh- where did they go?
Was there a pitfall? A mudslide?
No, the snow definitely hasn't moved.
Am I... have I been hallucinating this whole time?

I look back at the note. Crunch it between my fingers. No, this is real. This is undeniable. I know the textures of different papers like the back of my own hand. I could tell you at exactly what degree this would burst into flame.
What was I even doing here? What was I spending my time on?
I assumed we would get home. What would be the purpose of my proselytizing otherwise? But I never got a word in. I overstayed my welcome, I annoyed them all, and it led nowhere. And now they're gone.
And I'm here, in a mountain. Dark. A foot of snow beneath my feet. Empty tents. A cold machine.
I'm going to die like this.
Not if I... no, it's just not safe. Is it? Could I...
I look around to see if there are any trees nearby.
My hands are getting more immobile by the second.
There are no trees nearby.
Viotto hears a sigh from inside his head.
He looks back and digs beneath the snow to check the composition of the dirt.
No reaction to the sigh. It's non-notable.
"The dirt? Come on. Your thing is living animals, right? All that'll be down there is bones. You too, if you don't head somewhere warmer."

"The tablet is in deep snow, likely soaked through with melted water by now. If the ground is sufficiently saturated with anything like woodchips or intermittent bone marrow, and attempting to turn it on causes a connective shortage, it could easily begin to smoulder, akin to a coal-seam fire. Not to mention the possibility of an *actual* coal-seam fire."
He inspects the dirt.

"Viotto, I don't know if you understand the situation you're in. Fire would be a *goo*- No, never mind, that's obviously a non-starter."

"The tablet's gone."

"I have no evidence for that, although whatever allowed my targets to escape could have equally affected the tablet. I assume they were far enough away for this not to be the case, considering it didn't affect me. The slide would have been quite local. I don't know why I would entertain that thought."
"They went to another world, Viotto. Were you paying attention to that whole lecture?"

Viotto frowns. His thought process is getting a bit confusing, not that that's new. He considers lying down for a quick nap and wonders if his current location would be a good spot. Snow seems rather soft, especially when it's, like... packed? Not... frozen... eh, he doesn't know any snow terminology. It seems soft.
Man, his fingers just can't move anymore. Wild.
"Viotto, it's Entera. I don't know how I'd even begin to explain, but listen to me."

((tempted to write 'Viotto passes out' because that was my planned reaction to any Entera introduction but. I do not want to die session 2. and this is an extenuating version of an 'introduction' so I'll allow it))
I'm too tired to resist my intrusive thoughts.

"There's nobody within miles and miles of you. You have no means of contacting for help. You could maybe survive longer if you entered shelter, but hunger would still do you in. There's only one way I can think of for you to get out of this alive, and even that isn't a guarantee. You need to check the rightmost tent."
It does occur to me that I only ever saw the interior of two of the tents. It's a good idea. Glad I thought of it.
I go and check out the tent.
"Which one of these beds was Klaud in??? Agh, it doesn't matter. Check them both. There might be something."

I have no idea why a teacher would have anything useful on them, and there is no reason to assume they wouldn't have taken it with them if they did. I check the bed on the right, hoping it's not the one Klaud was in.

There is another tablet.

"Yes! Fuck yes." ((Entera was certainly not very vulgar back when you knew her.)) "Okay, give me a second."
I rush out of the *canvas tent* as quickly as possible after grabbing it. It takes all of my willpower not to mimic the original tablet's trajectory.
I leave the tablet on the edge of the lava-lamp looking thing and go back to check the other bed.
"No, don't-- okay, whatever. I don't think there should be anything in the other bed, anyway, but you can check if you'd like."
I check the other bed.
((Roll investigation))
There's nothing in the other bed.
No matter. Although in some sense redundant, I now begin my search for the other tablet I threw into the snow. I prefer to have everything in one place before working.
“Again, it’s not there. It went to the place you’re ‘supposed’ to be. Go back to the tablet you took out of the tent. …Please.”
"How arrogant. To believe that the idea of you holds some sway over my psyche. Begone, witch!" Viotto shoos at some piece of air and generally waves his cane around.
After a few seconds he goes back to the tablet by the LLLT.
It is still there.
Such a thing is foreign to him. I extend the rubber tip of my cane out to it and prod at what I assume is the screen.
This does nothing.
He flips the cane around and tries the lacquered wooden end. God knows how these things work.
This does nothing.
I get down on all fours and crawl over to it.
This is just being extended far too long.
This does something. You’re now on all fours and closer to it.
I debate going through a charade of prodding it with my shoe or jacket buttons or something but decide it's just not ~~funny~~ efficient enough. I TAP the screen with a trembling finger.

As soon as he does this, this drawn out segment ends.

“…Like herding cats.”
Viotto is transported to a black void where he cannot move. Five seconds later, he wakes up staring at a stone ceiling. ((end chapter and session))
